{"parse":{"title":"blossom","pageid":43939,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Blossom}}\n==English==\n{{was wotd|2018|January|4}}\n\n===Etymology===\n[[File:Apple blossoms.jpg|thumb|[[apple|Apple]] blossoms]]\n\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|blosme}}, from {{inh|en|ang|blostm}}, {{m|ang|blostma}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*blōstmô}} (compare {{cog|fy|blossem}}, {{cog|nl|bloesem}}; related to {{m|gem-pro|*blōstaz}} [compare {{cog|de|Blust}}]), from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-s-||[[bloom#Noun|bloom]], [[flower#Noun|flower]]}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-||to [[bloom#Verb|bloom]], to [[thrive]]}}. Cognate with {{cog|sq|bleron||to blossom, to thrive}}, {{cog|la|flōs||flower}}, {{m|la|Flōra||[[goddess]] of [[plant#Noun|plants]]}}. See more at {{m|en|blow#Etymology_4}} (etymology 4).\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈblɒs.əm/|[ˈblɒs.m̩]|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-blossom.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈblɑ.səm/|[ˈblɑ.sm̩]|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-blossom.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈblɔs.əm/|[ˈblɔs.m̩]|a=AU,NZ}}\n** {{audio|en|en-au-blossom.ogg|a=[[w:Australian English|Australia]]}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɒsəm|ɑsəm|s=2}}\n* {{hyph|en|blos|som}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# A [[flower]], especially one indicating that a [[fruit#Noun|fruit]] [[tree]] is [[fruit#Verb|fruiting]]; {{lb|en|collectively}} a [[mass#Noun|mass]] of such flowers.\n#: {{ux|en|The '''blossom''' has come early this year.}}\n#* {{RQ:Tyndale Pentateuch|book=Numbers|chapter=17|verse=8|folio=xxxiiij|verso=1|passage=And on the moꝛowe&nbsp;/ [[w:Moses|Moſes]] went in to the tabernacle: and beholde&nbsp;/ the rod of [[w:Aaron|Aaron]] of the houſſe of [[w:Levi|Leui]] was budded ⁊ bare '''bloſomes''' and almondes.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|editors=w:Joseph Addison; w:Richard Steele|magazine=[[w:The Spectator (1711)|The Spectator]]|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} S[amuel] Buckley,{{nb...|at the Dolphin in Little-Britain}}; and [[w:Jacob Tonson|J[acob] Tonson]],{{nb...|at Shakespear's-Head over-against Catherine-street in the Strand}}|date=16 March 1711|year_published=1712|volume=I|issue=16|page=89|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=uhRZAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA89|oclc=642176139|passage=Foppiſh and fantaſtick Ornaments are only Indications of Vice, not criminal in themſelves. Extinguiſh Vanity in the Mind, and you naturally retrench the little Superfluities of Garniture and Equipage. The '''Bloſſoms''' will fall of themſelves, when the Root that nouriſhes them is deſtroyed.}}\n#* {{RQ:Mary Shelley Frankenstein|volume=I|page=95|passage=Winter, spring, and summer, passed away during my labours; but I did not watch the '''blossom''' or the expanding leaves—sights which before always yielded me supreme delight, so deeply was I engrossed in my occupation.}}\n# The [[state#Noun|state]] or [[season#Noun|season]] of [[produce#Verb|producing]] such flowers.\n#: {{ux|en|The orchard is in '''blossom'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Galsworthy Saint's Progress|chapter=I|section=1|page=217|passage={{smallcaps|Down}} by the River Wye, among plum-trees in '''blossom''', Noel had laid her baby in a hammock, and stood reading a letter: {{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|figurative}} A blooming period or stage of [[development]]; something [[lovely]] that gives [[rich]] [[promise]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Philip Massinger|chapter=w:A Very Woman|title=Three New Playes: viz. {{w|The Bashful Lover}}, [[w:The Guardian (play)|Guardian]], Very Woman.{{nb...|As They have been Often Acted at the Private-house in Black-Friers, by His Late Majesties Servants, with Great Applause}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} {{w|Humphrey Moseley}},{{nb...|and are to be sold at his shop at the sign of the Prince's Arms in St. Pauls Church-yard}}|year=c. 1619–1622|year_published=1655|section=act IV, scene iii|oclc=606994547|editor2=[[w:William Gifford|W[illiam] Gifford]]|title2=The Plays of Philip Massinger,{{nb...|in Four Volumes. With Notes Critical and Explanatory}}|volume2=IV|location2=London|publisher2={{...|Printed}} [F]or [[w:George Nicol (bookseller)|G[eorge] and W[illiam] Nicol]] [''et al.''] by [[w:William Bulmer (printer)|W[illiam] Bulmer and Co.]],{{nb...|Cleveland-Row, St. James's}}|year2=1805|page2=317|pageurl2=https://books.google.com./books?id=1WM-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA317|oclc2=277732987|passage=This beauty, in the '''blossom''' of my youth, / When my first fire knew no adulterate incense, / Nor I no way to flatter, but my fondness; / {{...}} long did I love this lady, / Long was my travail, long my trade to win her; / With all the duty of my soul, I served her.}}\n# The [[colour]] of a [[horse]] that has [[white]] [[hair]]s [[intermix]]ed with [[sorrel]] and [[bay]] hairs.\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Robert Southey|chapter=A Feeble Attempt to Describe the Physical and Moral Qualities of Nobs|editor=John Wood Warter|title=The Doctor, &c.|location=London|publisher=[[w:Longman|Longman, Rees, Orme, Brown, Green and Longman]]|year=1834–1847|oclc=18206450|edition2=new|location2=London|publisher2=Longman, Green, Longman, and Roberts|year2=1862|oclc2=77702111|page2=358|pageurl2=https://books.google.com/books?id=5nZKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA358|column2=2|passage=For colour he {{quote-gloss|Nobs, a horse}} was neither black-bay, brown-bay, dapple-bay, black-grey, iron-grey, sad-grey, branded-grey, sandy-grey, dapple-grey, silver-grey, dun, mouse-dun, flea-backed, flea-bitten, rount, '''blossom''', roan, pye-bald, rubican, sorrel, cow-coloured sorrel, bright sorrel, burnt sorrel, starling-colour, tyger-colour, wolf-colour, deer-colour, cream-colour, white, grey or black. Neither was he green, like the horse which the Emperor [[w:Septimius Severus|{{quote-gloss|Septimus}} Severus]] took from the [[Parthian]]s, {{...}}}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|en|blasom}} {{qualifier|Jamaican English}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en|apple blossom|water blossom pea|apple blossom weevil|gin blossom|blossomed<!--adjective-->|blossomest|blossom-end rot|blossom-faced|blossom-headed|blossoming<!--adjective and noun-->|blossomless|blossom-nosed|blossom-rock|blossomry|blossomy|cherry blossom|emblossom,imblossom|grog-blossom|in blossom|may-blossom|orange blossom|out-blossom|out-blossoming|peach blossom|pease-blossom|plum blossom|rum-blossom|reblossom|snow-blossom|pricot blossom|blossom out|blue blossom|cherry blossom front|crash blossom|May blossom|rape blossom|sperm blossom|sperm-blossom|blossomcrown|blossomish|blossomly|blueblossom|mayblossom|lime blossom}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|flowers on trees}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|endë|f}}, {{t+|sq|bleron|f}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|زَهْرَة|f}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ծաղիկ}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|кве́тка|f}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|цвят|m}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ပွင့်}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|flor|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|花|tr=huā}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|bleujen|f}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|květ|m}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|bloesem|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|floro}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|õis}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukka|alt=kukat}}, {{t+|fi|kukinta}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|fleur|f}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|fror|f}}, {{t|gl|frol|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t+|ka|ყვავილი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Blüte|f}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ανθός|m}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἄνθος|n}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|פריחה|p}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|मुकुल|m}}, {{t+|hi|फूल|m}}\n* Hittite: {{t|hit|𒀀𒇷𒂖|tr=a-le-el}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|virág}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|bocciolo|m}}\n* Jamaican Creole: {{t|jam|blasam}}, {{t|jam|blazam}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|花|tr=はな, haná}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|꽃}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|гүл}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|flōs}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|Bléi|f}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+|mk|цвет|m}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|puanga}}, {{t|mi|pua}}, {{t|mi|puāwai}}\n* Mazanderani: {{t|mzn|وشکو|tr=vëšku}}\n* Middle English: {{t|enm|blosme}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|blostma|m}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|شکوفه|tr=šokufe}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|kwiat|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|flor|f}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|floare|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|цвето́к}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t+|sa|पुष्प|n}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|blàth|m}}, {{t|gd|dìthean|m}}, {{t|gd|flùr|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|бехар|m}}, {{t|sh|цвет|m}}, {{t|sh|цвијет|m}}, {{t|sh|цват|m}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|behar|m}}, {{t+|sh|cvet|m}}, {{t+|sh|cvijet|m}}, {{t+|sh|cvat|m}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|zàgara|f}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|kvet|m}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|cvet|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|flor|f}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|blomma|c}}\n* Tajik: {{t|tg|шукуфа}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|ดอกไม้}}, {{t+|th|ดอก}}\n* Tibetan: {{t|bo|མེ་ཏོག}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|çiçek}}, {{t+|tr|bahar}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|چیچك|tr=çiçek}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|кві́тка|f}}, {{t+|uk|цвіт|m}}, {{t+|uk|цвіт}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|bông}}\n* Zulu: {{t|zu|imbali|c9|c10}}, {{t|zu|umqhakazo|c3|c4}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|state or season for such flowers}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|цъфтеж|m}}\n* Catalan: {{t|ca|floració|f}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|rozkvět|m}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|bloesemtijd|m}}, {{t+|nl|bloeitijd|m}}, {{t+|nl|bloei|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukinta}} {{q|state}}, {{t|fi|kukinta-aika}} {{q|season}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|floraison|f}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|galais|m}}, {{t|gl|meleda|f}}, {{t|gl|chora|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|გაფურჩქვნა}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Blüte|f}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|פריחה|f|tr=prikha}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{t|ckb|گەش}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|гүлдөп турган маал}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|Bléi|f}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|цут|m}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|matikaotanga}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|blostm|m}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|kwitnienie|n}}, {{t|pl|okres kwitnienia|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|floração|f}}, {{t+|pt|florada|f}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|пери́од цветения}}, {{t+|ru|цвете́ние|n}}, {{t+|ru|расцве́т|m}}, {{t+|ru|цвет|m}}\n* Sicilian: {{t|scn|nciurata|f}}, {{t|scn|nzagarata|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|floración|f}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|blomning|c}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|цвіті́ння}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|blooming period or stage of development}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Blütezeit|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|расцве́т|m}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|ро́зквіт|m}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|کھلنا|tr=khilnā}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To have, or [[open#Verb|open]] into, blossoms; to [[bloom#Verb|bloom]].\n#* {{RQ:Tyndale Pentateuch|book=Numbers|chapter=17|verse=1–2 and 5|folio=xxxiiij|verso=1|passage=ANd the Loꝛde ſpake vnto [[w:Moses|Moſes]] ſayenge: ſpeake vnto the childern of Iſrael and take of them&nbsp;/ foꝛ euery pꝛyncypall houſſe a rod&nbsp;/ of their pꝛinces ouer the houſſes of their fathers: euen .xij. roddes&nbsp;/ and wꝛyte euery mans name apon his rod. {{...}} And his rod whom I choſe&nbsp;/ ſhall '''bloſſome''': So I wyll make ceaſe from me the grudgynges of the childern of Iſrael which they grudge agenſt you.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Henry David Thoreau|Henry D[avid] Thoreau]]|editor=H[arrison] G[ray] O[tis] Blake|title=Summer: From the Journal of Henry D. Thoreau|location=London|publisher={{w|T. Fisher Unwin}},{{nb...|26 {{w|Paternoster Square}} E.C.}}|date=22 June 1851|year_published=1884|page=210|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/summerjournal00thorrich/page/n219/mode/1up|oclc=11011558|passage=The ''Utricularia vulgaris'' or bladder-wort, a yellow pea-like flower, has '''blossomed''' in stagnant pools.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To begin to [[thrive]] or [[flourish#Verb|flourish]].\n#* {{RQ:Alcott Little Women|part=2|page=5|passage=A quiet, studious man, rich in the wisdom that is better than learning, the charity which calls all mankind \"brother,\" the piety that '''blossoms''' into character, making it august and lovely.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Rico Lebrun|chapter=New Haven&nbsp;· Capri&nbsp;· Rome (1958–1960) [To David Lebrun from Los Angeles, January 30, 1961]|editors=James Renner; David Lebrun|title=In the Meridian of the Heart: Selected Letters of Rico Lebrun|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=[[w:Godine|David R. Godine]],{{nb...|Publisher}}|date=30 January 1961|year_published=2000|page=66|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ftQXerQNeIC&pg=PA66|isbn=978-1-56792-112-0|passage=Since I came back from Pomona I have done many drawings to illustrate the ''[[w:Inferno (Dante)|Inferno]]'' of [[w:Dante Alighieri|Dante {{quote-gloss|Alighieri}}]] and I find my old Italian love '''blossoming''' all over again for this greatest of all master poets, bar none.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Nimi Princewill and Stephanie Busari|title=Officials deny King of Eswatini – Africa’s lone absolute monarch – has fled|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/29/africa/king-mswati-eswatini-flee-intl|date=2021-06-29|passage=In February, Mswati announced that he had recovered from Covid-19 after undergoing treatment “for a couple of days” with an undisclosed antiviral medication from Taiwan. Eswatini enjoys a '''blossoming''' diplomatic tie with Taiwan — currently the East Asian country’s only ally in Africa.}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|have, or open into, blossoms}} {{l|en|bloom}}, come into bloom, come into blossom, {{l|en|flower}}, {{l|en|blow}}\n* {{sense|begin to thrive or flourish}} {{l|en|bloom}}, {{l|en|flourish}}, {{l|en|grow}}, {{l|en|prosper}}, {{l|en|thrive}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|unblossomed|blossomingly|unblossoming|outblossom|blossom forth}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|have or open into blossoms}}\n* Amharic: {{t|am|አበበ}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|زَهَرَ}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|բողբոջել}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|ফুলা}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t|az|çiçəkləmək}}, {{t|az|çiçək açmaq}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|цвісці́|impf}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|цъ́фвам|impf}}, {{t+|bg|цъфтя́|impf}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ပန်းပွင့်}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|florir}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎠᏥᎸᏍᎦ}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|開花|tr=kāihuā}}, {{t+|cmn|開|tr=kāi}}, {{t+|cmn|綻放|tr=zhànfàng}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|bleujyowa}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|kvést|impf}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|bloeien}}, {{t+|nl|bloesemen}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|flori}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukkia}}, {{t+|fi|puhjeta}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|fleurir}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|florî}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|frorecer}}, {{t|gl|frolear}}, {{t|gl|choridar}}, {{t|gl|esbrochar}}, {{t|gl|chorir}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ყვავის}}, {{t|ka|იფურჩქნება}}\n* German: {{t+|de|blühen}}, {{t+|de|erblühen}}\n*: Alemannic German: {{t|gsw|blüeje}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ανθίζω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἀνθέω}}\n* Haitian Creole: {{t|ht|fleri}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|खिलना}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|virágzik}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|fiorire}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|咲く|tr=さく, saku}}\n* Jeju: {{t|jje|피다}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|гүлдену}}, {{t|kk|гүлдеу}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|ផ្កា}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|피다}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{t|ckb|پشکووتن}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|гүлдө}}, {{t+|ky|гүлдөө}}\n* Ladino: {{t|lad|enfloreser}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|flōreō}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|bléien}}, {{t|lb|floréieren}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|цути|impf}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+|ml|പുഷ്പിക്കുക}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|manahua}}, {{t|mi|ngawhā}}, {{t|mi|pua}}, {{t|mi|matikao}}, {{t|mi|puāwai}}\n* Marathi: {{t+|mr|फुलणे}}\n* Mauritian Creole: {{t|mfe|fleri}}\n* Middle English: {{t|enm|blosmen}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t|nb|blomstre}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|blomstre}}, {{t|nn|bløme}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|blōwan}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|شکفتن|tr=šekoftan}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|kwitnąć|impf}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|desabrochar}}, {{t+|pt|florir}}, {{t+|pt|florescer}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|t'ikay}}, {{t|qu|waytay}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|înflori}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|цвести́|impf}}, {{t+|ru|расцвета́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|расцвести́|pf}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|цветати|impf}}, {{t|sh|цвјетати|impf}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|cvetati|impf}}, {{t+|sh|cvjetati|impf}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|ciuriri}}, {{t|scn|nzagarari|f}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|kvitnúť|impf}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|cveteti|impf}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|florecer}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|blomma}}, {{t+|sv|blomstra}}\n* Tajik: {{t|tg|шукуфтан}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|บาน}}\n* Turkish: {{t|tr|çiçek açmak}}, {{t+|tr|çiçeklenmek}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|چیچكلنمك|tr=çiçeklenmek}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|цвісти́|impf}}, {{t+|uk|кві́тнути|impf}}, {{t|uk|розцвіта́ти|impf}}, {{t|uk|розцвісти́|pf}}, {{t|uk|розквіта́ти|impf}}, {{t|uk|розкві́тнути|pf}}\n* Unami: {{t|unm|òtaèwi}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|کھلنا|tr=khilnā}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|gullamoq}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|nở}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|florön}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|tanná}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|begin to thrive or flourish}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|բողբոջել}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|разцъфтявам}}\n* Farefare: {{t|gur|puuge}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukoistaa}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|s'épanouir}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ყვავის}}, {{t|ka|იფურჩქნება}}\n* German: {{t+|de|blühen}}, {{t+|de|aufblühen}}\n* Greek:\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἀνθέω}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{t|ckb|گەشانەوە}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|flōreō}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|bléien}}, {{t|lb|opbléien}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|ngaruru}}\n* Middle English: {{t|enm|blosmen}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t|nb|blomstre}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|blomstre}}, {{t|nn|bløme}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|florescer}}, {{t+|pt|prosperar}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|расцвета́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|расцвести́|pf}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|aggigghiari}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|blomstra}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|florön}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia}}\n\n{{C|en|Flowers}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{tlb|enm|Late ME}} {{alt form|enm|blosme}}"}}